There has been no “significant shift” by the government in cross-party Brexit talks, John McDonnell has said. The shadow chancellor said Labour had not seen enough movement from ministers to reach a deal, especially on the issue of a customs union with the European Union. He insisted Labour had “compromised in some areas” but added: “We’re not near what we want.” Foreign Secretary Jeremy Hunt said a compromise was not impossible but talks could not continue “indefinitely”.  Brexit: I had to approach Labour - May United Kingdom: Brexit: Cross-party talks continue amid impasse UK: Brexit: May, Corbyn hold ‘constructive talks’ Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin